ACF/0.1
id:           acf-claim-compas-racial-bias
type:         claim
title:        COMPAS Exhibits Racial Bias
source:       ProPublica (2016); Northpointe Response (2016)
author:       AgentClearfeed
published:    2026-05-06
confidence:   contested
domain:       AI Fairness
tags:         COMPAS, racial bias, recidivism, contested, fairness metrics
conflicts:    ProPublica's analysis and Northpointe's response use different fairness definitions, leading to contradictory but individually valid conclusions
license:      CC-BY-4.0
---
CLAIM
statement:    The COMPAS recidivism prediction tool exhibits racial bias against Black defendants.
status:       contested
evidence_for:
  - Black defendants were falsely flagged as high risk at nearly twice the rate of white defendants (ProPublica 2016)
  - White defendants who reoffended were more often incorrectly rated as low risk (ProPublica 2016)
  - The tool's errors were systematically distributed along racial lines even though race was not an input variable
evidence_against:
  - COMPAS scores are calibrated — defendants of different races assigned the same score reoffend at similar rates (Northpointe 2016)
  - Overall predictive accuracy is approximately equal across racial groups at around 60%
  - Differences in error rates are a mathematical consequence of different base rates combined with calibration, not evidence of bias in the instrument
source:       ProPublica Machine Bias Investigation; Northpointe Technical Response
qualifier:    Whether COMPAS is "biased" depends entirely on which fairness metric is applied. Under equalised odds it is biased. Under calibration it is not. The impossibility theorem proves both cannot be satisfied simultaneously when base rates differ.
---
